description:
Emma Grede is the founding partner behind the globally successful brands like SKIMS with Kim Kardashian, Good American with Khlo Kardashian, and Safely with Kris Jenner. She was named one of Forbes Richest Self-Made Women in America.

 How to build a winning brand strategy in 2025, what actually works in todays market
The key hiring traits behind her billion-dollar teams and why grit and adaptability beat experience
 Why hustle culture isnt toxic and how ambition fuels Emmas business growth and company culture
The leadership frameworks she uses to scale fast and build high-performance, mission-driven teams
How she grew SKIMS and Good American without design skills: by doubling down on vision, execution, and speed
Why every founder must zoom out and audit their business regularly, or risk scaling failure instead of success

comments.text: @Steven - Overall another great interview but I would have liked you to be more measured about the impact of prejudice, in particular stereotype threat. From your recollection of Aronson & Steeles (1995) study you asserted that "stereotype threat is a real thing".  But one study doesnt make a psychological phenomenon a real thing. Stereotype threat has had problems with replication. Large scale meta-analysis suggest the effects of stereotype threat range from negligible to small.  Prominent social psychologist Lee Jussim, an expert on stereotypes, has said research on stereotype threat may be flawed, possibly due to methodological issues or questionable interpretive practices. Your guest Emma followed your lead by saying, it's undoubtable that its real for so many people. Undoubtable? How quickly feelings and facts get muddled, especially when psychological data and studies are inexpertly introduced. Giving you the benefit of the doubt, I think the point of brining up stereotype threat was simply to point out that people shouldnt so quickly doubt and limit themselves based on what others may think. A point with which I wholeheartedly agree. But, for a topic as charged and as fraught as prejudice, please take care and be a bit more circumspect with how you bring in evidence to make your case in the future. Other than that, really enjoyed the interview, thank you.
comments.author: @nathana.9120

comments.text:
Steven, please talk to some men about fertility. 

The overwhelming majority of men believe that women have a finite number of eggs, men can make sperm forever, therefore only women have a fertility window. ::sarcastic clapping for Robert DeNiro and Al Pacino::. Fuller picture: the quality of sperm is based on the quality of your DNA. DNA degrades as we age - thats what biological aging *is*. 

So a man can produce sperm that will fertilize an egg at 50, 60, even beyond. But your genetic code at 25 - thats what DNA is: the code that tells the body how to function - is not the same quality as it will be at 60. If a man has a child at 60, the baby receives all of the coding errors that have accumulated over 60 years of aging.

Men really dont want to think or talk about this, understandably. It touches on aging, mortality, and ideas of virility. No one wants to consider that their childs genetic defects and any resulting health problems were caused by their own DNA. But if you want to inform people about fertility choices, male aging has to be discussed, too.

Signed, a gerontologist.

::hops off soapbox::

comments.text:
Work-life balance is crucial. 
Considering her role in sales, marketing, and leadership, I understand her perspective. However, for her to excel, she can't do it alone; she relies on her team to achieve success. When team members put in effort but only see a 10% bonus or 5% salary increase, it underscores the need for work-life balance to prevent burnout and foster creativity, ultimately benefiting the business. 
While she is an extrovert, it's important to note that many data professionals are introverts. Events in the office meant for team bonding can be quite draining for them, as they often prefer minimal social interaction. I work with data and manage a portfolio that leads in market share because I work from home. A trip to the office requires me to take a day to recover. My portfolio generates more revenue than many of my colleagues, including extroverted ones. 
Introverts bring significant value as well. She dislikes the work-life balance question during interviews, yet I feel this approach lacks a genuine understanding of diversity and empathy. I, too, ask this question because I've experienced burnout and disappointment. I worked hard, delivered profits, and received bonuses and pay raises. However, when I needed the promised support during a vulnerable timeafter returning from my first maternity leave while dealing with postpartum depression during COVID and coping with the unexpected loss of my father to cancerI found that support lacking, which left me feeling burned out. 
It's critical to have clarity about the flexibility available without facing repercussions. 
While conditions at my company have improved, it took a collective complaint from myself and several colleagues to drive that change, which was a traumatic experience for me. 
I ask about work-life balance; I want to know what I'm getting into. After COVID, we cannot continue working as we did before. I have children and want to be present for them, cherishing these moments as they grow up too quickly. I have a beautiful life with a house, a family, and holidays. My career is not my priority now.
